\f1\fs32 \cf3 \cb2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Java achieves the famous motto \'93Write Once, Run Anywhere\'94 (WORA) because it is designed to be\'a0
\f2\b platform-independent
\f1\b0 , even though the environment that runs it is platform-dependent.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 Although the JVM was originally built for Java, it is now a\'a0
\f2\b language-independent platform
\f1\b0 . Any programming language that can be compiled into Java bytecode can run on the JVM\
\
Here is the step-by-step process of how your code actually runs:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \

\f2\b\fs40  A) The Compilation Phase (The \'93Translator\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 You write your code in a\'a0
\f3\fs28 \cb4 .java
\f1\fs32 \cb2 \'a0file. You then run the Java Compiler (
\f3\fs28 \cb4 javac
\f1\fs32 \cb2 ). This is the first \'93translator.\'94 It checks your syntax and translates your human-readable code into\'a0
\f2\b Bytecode
\f1\b0 \'a0(a\'a0
\f3\fs28 \cb4 .class
\f1\fs32 \cb2 \'a0file).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f4\i \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Crucial Point:
\f1\i0 \'a0This step happens only once before you ship your app.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \cb2 \

\f2\b\fs40  B) The Loading Phase\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 When you run the program, the\'a0
\f2\b JVM
\f1\b0 \'a0loads that\'a0
\f3\fs28 \cb4 .class
\f1\fs32 \cb2 \'a0file into memory. At this stage, the code is still bytecode\'97it\'92s not yet something your CPU understands.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \

\f2\b\fs40  C)The Interpretation Phase (The \'93Interpreter\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 Inside the JVM, there is an\'a0
\f2\b Interpreter
\f1\b0 . It starts reading the bytecode line-by-line and translates it into machine-specific instructions (native machine code) on the fly.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Pro:
\f1\b0 \'a0It starts the program almost instantly.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Con:
\f1\b0 \'a0Reading and translating line-by-line is relatively slow.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \cb2 \

\f2\b\fs40  D) The JIT Compilation Phase (The \'93Optimizer\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 This is where Java gets its speed. As the interpreter runs, a component called the\'a0
\f2\b Just-In-Time (JIT) Compiler
\f1\b0 \'a0watches the code.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
If it sees a specific block of code (like a loop or a method) being run repeatedly (a \'93hot spot\'94), it stops interpreting it.\cb1 \
\ls3\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Instead, the JIT compiles that entire block into\'a0
\f2\b native machine code
\f1\b0  and saves it.\cb1 \
\ls3\ilvl0\cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The next time that code is needed, the JVM skips the interpreter and runs the high-speed machine code directly.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \cb2 \

\f2\b\fs40 Summary of the Flow:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\fs32 \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Source Code
\f1\b0 \'a0(
\f3\fs28 \cb4 .java
\f1\fs32 \cb2 ) -> 
\f2\b Compiler -> Bytecode
\f1\b0 \'a0(
\f3\fs28 \cb4 .class
\f1\fs32 \cb2 ).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf3 \cb1 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}
\f2\b \cb2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Bytecode -> JVM Interpreter
\f1\b0 \'a0(starts running code line-by-line)\
\ls4\ilvl0\cb1 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}
\f2\b \cb2 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Hot Bytecode -> JIT Compiler -> Native Machine Code
\f1\b0 \'a0(runs directly on the hardware for max speed)\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb1 \
Interpretor and JIT\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf3 {\listtext	
\f2\b\fs40 \cb2 1.	}
\f1\b0\fs32 \cb1 The Interpreter (The \'93Live Translator\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \cb2 Think of the Interpreter like a\'a0
\f2\b live language translator
\f1\b0 \'a0at a conference.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Action:
\f1\b0 \'a0It hears one sentence in Bytecode, whispers the translation in \'93Native Machine Code\'94 to the CPU, and then\'85\'a0
\f2\b it immediately forgets it.
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Problem:
\f1\b0 \'a0If the speaker says that same sentence 100 times, the interpreter has to manually translate it 100 times. That is a lot of wasted effort.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 \cb2 \
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf3 {\listtext	1.	}    
\f2\b 2
\f1\b0 . The JIT Compiler (The \'93Note Taker\'94)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf3 The JIT (Just-In-Time) Compiler is like a translator who notices a specific phrase is being used over and over.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Action:
\f1\b0 \'a0It stops, writes the translation down on a piece of paper (
\f2\b saves it in memory
\f1\b0 ), and hands it to the CPU.\cb1 \
\ls8\ilvl0
