\f2\b\fs40 \cf3 \cb2 1. What is a Sandbox?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 Think of a\'a0
\f2\b Sandbox
\f1\b0 \'a0as a restricted "play area" for a program. When Java runs code (especially from the internet, like old-school applets), the JVM puts it in a box.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Restriction:
\f1\b0 \'a0The code can play with its own toys (its own memory), but it cannot touch your computer's files, cameras, or network without explicit permission.\cb1 \
\ls12\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Security:
\f1\b0 \'a0If the code turns out to be malicious, it can "explode" inside the box, but your actual operating system remains safe.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

