\f2\b\fs40 \cf3 2. How Pointers Impact Security\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf3 In languages like C++,\'a0
\f2\b pointers
\f1\b0 \'a0are variables that store the exact physical address of a memory location.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Risk:
\f1\b0 \'a0If a programmer makes a mistake (or a hacker is clever), they can use a pointer to "jump" into a memory space they shouldn't have access to\'97like where your passwords or OS kernel data are stored.\cb1 \
\ls13\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Java\'92s Solution:
\f1\b0 \'a0Java\'a0
\f2\b removed explicit pointers.
\f1\b0 \'a0You cannot see or manipulate memory addresses. Java uses "References," which let you talk to objects, but the JVM manages where they actually live in the hardware. This prevents "Buffer Overflow" attacks, a common way hackers take over systems.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

