\f6\b \cf0 2. How the "Rules" Run the Code (Implementation)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 You correctly noted that a "set of rules" (JVM Spec) can't run code. Here is how it physically happens:\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls22\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Software on Disk (JRE):
\f5\b0  A company (like Oracle) writes a software program in a language like C/C++ that follows every rule in the JVM Specification.\
\ls22\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Execution:
\f5\b0  When you run 
\f3 \cb6 java MyProgram
\f5 \cb1 , the OS launches that software.\
\ls22\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Translation:
\f5\b0  That software (now a "JVM Instance" in memory) looks at your bytecode. It says, 
\f8\i "The rules say instruction 0x60 means 'Add'. I will now tell the CPU to perform an addition."
\f5\i0 \
\ls22\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Libraries:
\f5\b0  If your code asks to "Open a Window," the JVM looks in the 
\f6\b JRE Libraries
\f5\b0 . These libraries contain the specific "native" code needed to talk to your specific Operating System.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf7 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 3. Why Multiple Companies have JDKs (Distributions)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 Since the 
\f6\b JVM Specification
\f5\b0  and the 
\f6\b OpenJDK
\f5\b0  source code are open to the public. Then different vendors "build" their own versions of the JDK.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls23\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
OpenJDK:
\f5\b0  The "master" open-source code. Most companies use this as their starting point.\
\ls23\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Oracle JDK:
\f5\b0  The commercial version. It\'92s highly stable and often used by big banks/enterprises who pay for Oracle's official support.\
\ls23\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Amazon Corretto:
\f5\b0  Amazon\'92s build. They optimized it for their cloud (AWS) and offer it for free with long-term security updates.\
\ls23\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Azul Zulu:
\f5\b0  Specialized in "extra-long" support. They keep very old versions of Java (like Java 7) alive and secure for companies that can't upgrade their old software yet.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \
The "Safety Valve": TCK\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 To ensure an app written on an Amazon JDK doesn't crash on an Oracle JVM, every vendor must pass the 
\f6\b TCK (Technology Compatibility Kit)
\f5\b0 . This is a massive suite of thousands of tests. If a company's JDK passes, it is officially "Java-compatible."\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls24\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Distributions
\f5\b0  (Oracle, Azul, etc.) are just different "brands" of the same toolbox, all verified to work identically by the TCK.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
