\cf0 \AppleHighlight-1 Here is the breakdown of how a Java program starts and why the 
\f3 \cb6 main
\f5 \cb1  method is designed the way it is.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \
1. The Entry Point: public static void main(String[] args)\
T
\f5\b0 he Entry Point is the specific place where the JVM starts executing your code.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa331\partightenfactor0
\ls25\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \AppleHighlight0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\AppleHighlight-1 - Who calls it? The JVM calls it. When you run java MyClass, the JVM looks specifically for a method with this exact signature to start the program.\
\ls25\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \AppleHighlight0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\AppleHighlight-1 - The Arguments (String[] args): These are Command Line Arguments. They allow you to pass information into your program when you start it.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0
\cf0     Example: If you run java MyClass Hello 123, then args[0] will be "Hello" and args[1] will be "123".\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \
2. Why must 
\f9 \cb6 main
\f6 \cb1  be 
\f9 \cb6 static
\f6 \cb1 ?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 This is the "chicken and egg" problem of Java.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls26\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Logic:
\f5\b0  To call a 
\f6\b non-static
\f5\b0  method, you must first create an 
\f6\b object
\f5\b0  of that class using the 
\f3 \cb6 new
\f5 \cb1  keyword.\
\ls26\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Problem:
\f5\b0  If the 
\f3 \cb6 main
\f5 \cb1  method were not static, the JVM would have to create an object of your class 
\f8\i before
\f5\i0  the program even starts.\
\ls26\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The Solution:
\f5\b0  By making it 
\f3 \cb6 static
\f5 \cb1 , the JVM can call the method using only the 
\f6\b Class Name
\f5\b0  (e.g., 
\f3 \cb6 MyClass.main()
\f5 \cb1 ) without needing to allocate memory for an object first. It keeps the startup process simple and memory-efficient.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls26\ilvl0
\f8\i \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\i0\b \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
3. Can we have multiple 
\f9 \cb6 main
\f6 \cb1  methods?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Yes, in two ways:
\f5\b0 \
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls27\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Overloading:
\f5\b0  You can have multiple methods named 
\f3 \cb6 main
\f5 \cb1  in the 
\f8\i same
\f5\i0  class, but they must have different arguments (e.g., 
\f3 \cb6 main(int a)
\f5 \cb1 ). However, the JVM will 
\f6\b only
\f5\b0  ever call the one with the 
\f3 \cb6 String[] args
\f5 \cb1  signature as the starting point.\
\ls27\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Different Classes:
\f5\b0  Every single class in your project can have its own 
\f3 \cb6 public static void main
\f5 \cb1  method. When you run the program, you tell the JVM which class to look in. This is often used for writing "test code" inside individual classes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \
4. What are Variable Arguments (Varargs)?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 Introduced in Java 5, 
\f6\b Varargs
\f5\b0  allow a method to accept zero or many arguments of the same type.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls28\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Syntax:
\f5\b0  Use three dots 
\f3 \cb6 ...
\f5 \cb1  (e.g., 
\f3 \cb6 int... numbers
\f5 \cb1 ).\
\ls28\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How it works:
\f5\b0  Inside the method, Java treats the varargs as an 
\f6\b array
\f5\b0 .\
\ls28\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Why use it?
\f5\b0  It makes the code cleaner. Instead of manually creating an array to pass to a method, you can just list the items: 
\f3 \cb6 sum(1, 2, 3, 4)
\f5 \cb1 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 Example of Varargs in a main-like style:
\f5\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f3 \cf8 \cb6 public\cf0  \cf8 static\cf0  \cf8 void\cf0  myMethod(String... messages) \{\
    \cf8 for\cf0  (\cf8 String\cf0  \cf9 s\cf0  : messages) \{\
        System.out.println(\cf10 s\cf0 );\
    \}\
\}\

\f10\i \cf11 // You can call it as: myMethod("Hi", "Hello", "Hey");
\f3\i0 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \cb1 Note for your notes:
\f5\b0  You can actually write the main method as 
\f3 \cb6 public static void main(String... args)
\f5 \cb1  and it will work perfectly because 
\f6\b Varargs
\f5\b0  are just a "fancier" way to write an array!\
Would you like to see how the 
\f6\b Class Loader
\f5\b0  specifically finds this 
\f3 \cb6 main
\f5 \cb1  method among thousands of classes?\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
