\f6\b \cf0 3. Why Use Modularity? (The Problems it Fixes)\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls30\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Encapsulation (Privacy):
\f5\b0  You can hide "internal" code. Even if a class is 
\f3 \cb13 public
\f5 \cb1 , it is invisible to other modules unless you explicitly 
\f6\b export
\f5\b0  it.\
\ls30\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Dependency Management:
\f5\b0  It stops "Classpath Hell." The system ensures no two modules export the same package (
\f6\b No Split Packages
\f5\b0 ).\
\ls30\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Reduced Size (jlink):
\f5\b0  You can create a 
\f6\b Custom JRE
\f5\b0  that only includes the parts of Java your app actually needs (e.g., removing 3D graphics or XML modules), making cloud deployments much smaller.\
\ls30\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Reliability:
\f5\b0  Conflicts (like missing libraries or circular dependencies) are caught at 
\f6\b startup or test-time
\f5\b0  rather than crashing randomly in production.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 4. Key Terms for Notes\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls31\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Module Descriptor (
\f9 \cb13 module-info.java
\f6 \cb1 ):
\f5\b0  The file that defines what a module 
\f6\b requires
\f5\b0  (needs) and 
\f6\b exports
\f5\b0  (shares).\
\ls31\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Strong Encapsulation:
\f5\b0  The JVM\'92s ability to block reflection or access to internal packages.\
\ls31\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Modular Monolith:
\f5\b0  A single-project approach (like Spring Modulith) that uses strict package boundaries to keep code clean without the complexity of multiple JAR files.\
\ls31\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Fat JAR vs. Slim JRE:
\f5\b0  Spring Boot usually builds a "Fat JAR" (all libraries inside), while Modularity allows for a "Slim JRE" (minimal Java engine).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 5. Professional Reality Check\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls32\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 In 
\f6\b Spring Boot
\f5\b0 , developers rarely use 
\f3 \cb13 module-info.java
\f5 \cb1  because it clashes with reflection.\
\ls32\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Instead, "Modularity" in a dev career usually means 
