\f6\b\fs36 \cf0 1. How does the JIT "know" a block is repeated?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 The JIT doesn't just read the code; it 
\f6\b watches
\f5\b0  the code. Inside the JVM, there are 
\f6\b counters
\f5\b0  attached to every method and loop in your bytecode.\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls33\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 The Counter System:
\f5\b0  Every time the Interpreter runs a method or a loop, the JVM increments a counter for that specific block.\
\ls33\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 The Threshold:
\f5\b0  The JVM has a "heat" threshold (e.g., 10,000 calls).\
\ls33\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 The Trigger:
\f5\b0  Once a counter hits that number, the JVM marks that code as 
\f6\b "Hot."
\f5\b0 \
\ls33\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 The JIT Action:
\f5\b0  Only then does the JIT Compiler step in. It takes that specific "Hot" bytecode, optimizes it heavily (like a master craftsman), and turns it into high-speed 
\f6\b Native Machine Code
\f5\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \strokec12 2. Does the JVM read and hand it to the Interpreter?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 Yes, exactly! Think of the 
\f6\b JVM
\f5\b0  as the "Manager" and the 
\f6\b Interpreter
\f5\b0  as the "Worker."\
\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls34\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Loading:
\f5\b0  The JVM (Manager) reads the 
\f3 \cb13 .class
\f5 \cb1  file from your disk.\
\ls34\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Feeding:
\f5\b0  The JVM hands the bytecode stream to the 
\f6\b Interpreter
\f5\b0  (Worker).\
\ls34\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Execution:
\f5\b0  The Interpreter reads a line, translates it, and executes it immediately.\
\ls34\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Monitoring:
\f5\b0  While the Interpreter is working, the JVM Manager is standing over its shoulder with a stopwatch and a counter, waiting to see which parts are worth sending to the 
\f6\b JIT Compiler
\f5\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \strokec12 The Full Step-by-Step Flow:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 JVM
\f5\b0  reads bytecode.\
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 JVM
\f5\b0  feeds bytecode to the 
\f6\b Interpreter
\f5\b0 .\
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Interpreter
\f5\b0  executes line-by-line + 
\f6\b JVM
\f5\b0  increments "heat counters."\
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Counter hits limit
\f5\b0  $\\rightarrow$ 
\f6\b JIT Compiler
\f5\b0  wakes up.\
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 JIT
\f5\b0  compiles that block to Native Code and stores it in a special area called the 
\f6\b Code Cache
\f5\b0 .\
\ls35\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Next time:
\f5\b0  The JVM sees the call, skips the Interpreter, and runs the 
\f6\b Native Code
\f5\b0  from the cache directly.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa331\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \strokec12 Summary for your Notes:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls36\ilvl0
\f6\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Interpreter:
\f5\b0  The "First Responder." It starts immediately but is slow because it repeats work.\
\ls36\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 Counters:
\f5\b0  The "Thermometers" that tell the JVM which code is "hot" (frequently used).\
\ls36\ilvl0
\f6\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec12 JIT:
\f5\b0  The "Optimizer." It only works on hot code to save time and energy, turning it into permanent, fast machine code.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\b \cf0 \strokec12 Wait, doesn't compiling code while the program is running slow it down?
\f5\b0  Actually, the JIT usually runs on a 
\f6\b separate background thread
\f5\b0  (Parallelism!) so your program doesn't freeze while the optimization is happening.\

